Charisse studied ballet as a child, and began her film career in the 1940s. Her dancing caught the attention of Choreographer Robert Alton \u2014who also discovered #GeneKelly, and she was signed to Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer, where she was the resident MGM ballet dancer, and  quickly became much more! \nCharisse appeared in several films with both Fred Astair and Gene Kelly, including \"Singin' in the Rain\" (1952), \"The Band Wagon\" (1953), \"Brigadoon\" (1954), and \"Silk Stockings\" (1957), for which she was nominated for a Golden Globes and a Golden Laurel. \nShe was awarded the National Medal of the Arts and Humanities in 2006, which was presented to her by President and Mrs. Laura Bush in an Oval Office ceremony. Ms. Charisse's citation reads, \"An American icon, she has entertained millions throughout her career with her many stunning performances.\" \n\nIn her autobiography, Charisse wrote about dancing with both Astair and Kelly. \"As one of the handful of girls who worked with both of those dance geniuses, I think I can give an honest comparison. In my opinion, Kelly is the more inventive choreographer of the two. Astaire, with Hermes Pan's help, creates fabulous numbers\u2014for himself and his partner. But Kelly can create an entire number for somebody else ... I think, however, that Astaire's coordination is better than Kelly's ... his sense of rhythm is uncanny. Kelly, on the other hand, is the stronger of the two. When he lifts you, he lifts you! ... To sum it up, I'd say they were the two greatest dancing personalities who were ever on screen. But it's like comparing apples and oranges.
